      <hedline>
        <hl1>Toward Better Care for the Old</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Leter from Len Fishman, American Assn of Homes and Services for the Aging president, says Congress must enact enforceable nursing home staffing standard on state Medicaid programs and restore damaging cuts made in 1997 to Medicare program (Aug 7 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Acceptable Nursing Home Care'' (editorial, Aug. 7):</p>
        <p>Getting Congress and the states to appropriate money so nursing homes can compete for the staff they need will not be easy. The only beneficiaries of nursing homes' low staff levels are federal and state treasuries, because reimbursement is tied to staffing levels. Lower staff means lower payments by government.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Acceptable Nursing Home Care'' (editorial, Aug. 7):</p>
        <p>Getting Congress and the states to appropriate money so nursing homes can compete for the staff they need will not be easy. The only beneficiaries of nursing homes' low staff levels are federal and state treasuries, because reimbursement is tied to staffing levels. Lower staff means lower payments by government.</p>
        <p>To make real progress on staffing levels, Congress must enact an enforceable standard on state Medicaid rates, which account for more than half of nursing home revenue.  Meanwhile, Congress should restore the damaging cuts made in 1997 to the Medicare program.</p>
        <p>LEN FISHMAN  President, American Association of Homes and Services for the Aging  Washington, Aug. 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
